ce:section.ce:para:
It is generally understood that the photocatalytic CO2 reduction reaction involves an interface reaction process: CO2 and H2O molecules diffuse to the catalyst surface to occupy the active sites, and then undergo subsequent redox reactions with the photogenerated electrons and holes. Hence, the specific surface area of semiconductor photocatalysts is a major concern for the photoreduction of CO2. The specific surface areas of the Bi4MoO9 and N-CQDs/Bi4MoO9 materials were determined using nitrogen adsorption–desorption isotherms. The adsorption hysteresis loops of the samples studied revealed that the adsorption types of Bi4MoO9 and N-CQDs/Bi4MoO9 materials were type IV isotherms (
                           Figure S5
                        ).[56] In addition, the Brunauer-Emmett-Teller (BET) specific surface areas of Bi4MoO9 and N-CQDs/Bi4MoO9-2 did not change. It can be tentatively inferred that the specific BET surface area may not be the main factor cause accelerating the photocatalytic process.
